.TH "CPortManagerException class" 3 0.1 NSCLDaq "NSCL DAQ C++ Packages"
.SH SYNOPSIS
.DS
#include <config.h>
#include <histotypes.h>
#include <CPortManagerException.h>


class CPortManagerException : public CException
{
public:
	typedef enum _Reason {
		NoPorts,
		NotLocal,
		ConnectionFailed
	} Reason;
public:
   CPortManagerException(string host,
			  Reason      why,
			  string doing);
    CPortManagerException(const CPortManagerException& rhs);			
    virtual ~CPortManagerException();
	
    CPortManagerException& operator=(const CPortManagerException& rhs);
    int operator==(const CPortManagerException& rhs);
    int operator!=(const CPortManagerException& rhs);

    virtual const char* ReasonText() const;
    virtual Int_t       ReasonCode() const;    
    static string  ReasonCodeToText(int code);
 	
};
// Handy stream put operator for formatting the exception.

ostream& operator<<(ostream& f, const CPortManagerException& e); 


.DE

add
.DS
-I/usr/opt/daq/current/include
.DE
to your compilation lines.

add
.DS
-L/usr/opt/daq/current/lib -lPortManager
.DE
to your link line.
.SH DESCRIPTION
.PP
\fBCPortManagerException\fR is an exception that can be thrown by the port
manager class \fBCPortManager\fR (see the man page for this class).  Since it
is descended from \fBCException\fR, it can be caught as a generic error.  In
addition to the base class members, the class supports insertion into an output
stream.
.SH "PUBLIC INTERFACE"
.PP 
This section assumes  you are not interested in throwing
CPortManagerExceptions, just in catching/interpreting them, although the
constructors should be relatively self explanatory.
.TP
virtual const char* \fBReasonText\fR() const;
Retrieves a pointer to a text string that describes why the exception was
thrown.
.TP
virtual Int_t \fBReasonCode\fR() const;
Returns an integerized version of the reason the exception was thrown.  This is
a cast of a \fBCPortManagerException::Reason\fR enum to int.  See SYNOPSIS for
the possible values of this enum.
.TP
static string \fBReasonCodeToText\fI(int code);
Returns a string that describes a value returned by
\fBCPortManagerException::ReasonCode\fR.
.TP
ostream& \fBoperator<<\fR(ostream& \fIf\fR, const CPortManagerException&
\fIe\fR);
produces a textual representation of the error condition described by the
exception \fIe\fR and outputs it to the stream \fIf\fR.
.SH EXAMPLES
.PP
The example below catches an exception.  If the exception was thrown because of
a Connection failure. it is just printed to cerr.  Otherwise, The reason text
is printed along with a message idicating that a port allocation failed.

.DS
 . . .
try {
 . . .
}
catch (CPortManagerException& e) {
   int why = e.ReasonCode();
   if((CPortManagerException::Reason)why == 
                   CPortManagerException::ConnectionFailed) {
      cerr << e << endl;
   }
   else {
      cerr << "Port Allocation Failed: " << e.ReasonText() << endl;
   }
}

 . . .
.DE

.SH BUGS
The stream insertion operator really should be done at the level of CException
with implementations delegated to an actual object's virtual implementation.
